# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: china-national-football-b-team
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:china-national-football-b-team/1956-chinese-national-olympic-football-trial] The **1956 Chinese National Olympic Football Trial** was a tournament held by the Chinese National Sport Committee to select the football representatives for the 1956 Summer Olympics.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/1956-chinese-national-olympic-football-trial] The United Red Team defeated United White Team in the final match and won the ticket to Melbourne.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/1956-chinese-national-olympic-football-trial] The National Team was split into the United Red and White teams, with members mostly made of the Chinese Youth Team returning from studying in Hungary.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/1956-chinese-national-olympic-football-trial] The National Sport Committee also invited Hong Kong, Macau and Taiwan to join Olympic trials, the invitation was denied by Taiwan, and Macau did not send a football team.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/1956-chinese-national-olympic-football-trial] In the opening match, Shanghai defeated Hong Kong with a 6-1 score.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/1956-chinese-national-olympic-football-trial] Hong Kong withdrew from the tournament next day and lost to Bayi with 0-7 in a friendly.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/1956-chinese-national-olympic-football-trial] Shanghai then lost to both the United Red and United White teams with the same 1-2 score.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/1956-chinese-national-olympic-football-trial] In the final match, United Red defeated United White 2-1.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/1956-chinese-national-olympic-football-trial] After the tournament, the United Red team was kept in Beijing and became the Beijing Football Team.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/1956-chinese-national-olympic-football-trial] The United White team was disbanded as a result.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/1956-chinese-national-olympic-football-trial] As the players were professional players, the team was led to Tianjian to found the Tianjian Football Team.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/1989-chinese-jia-a-league] Statistics of the Chinese Jia-A League for the 1989 season.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/1989-chinese-jia-a-league] It was contested by 8 teams, and China B won the championship.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/a1-team-china] The seat holder *A1 Team China* is Liu Yu (刘煜).
[src:china-national-football-b-team/a1-team-china] Werner Gillis is the team principal, and technical support is provided by Team Astromega.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/a1-team-china] A mixed bag of results for the team, culminated in 13th position, including a podium at one of the team's home races in Zhuhai.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/a1-team-china] Fortunes changed for Team China, as the mix of Cheng and Tung managed to lift the team to 15th position, as well as scoring a podium.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/a1-team-china] Team China were uncompetitive in the inaugural season, scoring points only once and finishing in 22nd position.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/a1-team-china] (key), "spr" indicate a Sprint Race, "fea" indicate a Main Race.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] The **Asian Football Confederation** (**AFC**) is the governing body of association football, beach soccer, and futsal in most countries and territories in Asia.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] It is one of the six continental confederations under FIFA and is responsible for organising international competitions for national teams and clubs within its jurisdiction, including the AFC Asian Cup and AFC Champions League Elite.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] Founded in 1954 and headquartered in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, the AFC comprises 47 member associations.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] The idea of an Asian Football Confederation was first brought up during the 1952 Summer Olympics in Helsinki, Finland.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] On 8 May 1954, the AFC was officially formed at the 1954 Asian Games in Manila, Philippines.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] The first president was Lo Man-kam of Hong Kong, and the first office was based in Hong Kong.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] The 13 founding members included Afghanistan, Burma, Hong Kong, India, Indonesia, Israel Japan, Pakistan, the Philippines, Singapore, South Korea, South Vietnam, and Taiwan.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] Of the AFC's original 13 member associations, only seven entered the qualifying tournament for the inaugural AFC Asian Cup in 1956.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] Four teams ultimately qualified for the final tournament, which was held in then-British Hong Kong.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] The 1956 tournament was the first edition of the AFC Asian Cup, the world's second-oldest continental national-team football competition.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] Arab countries entered the Asian Cup qualifiers for the first time in the 1972 AFC Asian Cup qualification, following Israel's withdrawal.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] Israel was eventually expelled from the AFC in 1974, due to political pressure from Arab and Muslim members that refused to play against Israel.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] In 1958, the office relocated from Hong Kong to Malaysia.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] In 2000, the AFC House was inaugurated as the AFC's headquarters; based in Bukit Jalil, Kuala Lumpur, the construction cost RM 18 million (US$ 8.18 million).
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] The Asian Ladies Football Confederation (ALFC) was the section of AFC that managed women's association football in Asia.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] The group was independently founded in April 1968 in a meeting involving Taiwan, British Hong Kong, Malaysia, and Singapore.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] On 1 February 2023, the AFC's member associations elected the AFC Executive Committee for the term 2023 to 2027.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] Including the AFC president, the AFC has seven members on the FIFA Council.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] The AFC organizes the AFC Asian Cup and the AFC Women's Asian Cup, both held every four years.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] It also runs the AFC Futsal Asian Cup, AFC Women's Futsal Asian Cup, and the AFC Beach Soccer Asian Cup, along with various youth and age-group international association football and futsal tournaments.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] In addition, the AFC oversees the Asian qualifying tournaments for the FIFA World Cup and for football at the Summer Olympics.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] The premier men's club competition is the AFC Champions League Elite, which is an amalgamation of the Asian Club Championship, the Asian Cup Winners' Cup, and the Asian Super Cup.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] It features leading clubs from AFC member associations, with the number of participating teams determined by the ranking of each association, allowing for promotion or relegation of slots based on performance.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] The top-tier women's club competition is the AFC Women's Champions League, introduced in the 2024–25 season.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] The second-tier men's club competition is the AFC Champions League Two, while the third tier is the AFC Challenge League, both of which were restructured and rebranded in 2024.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] The AFC also organizes the annual AFC Futsal Club Championship, the continent’s premier club futsal competition.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/asian-football-confederation] For each tournament, the flag of the host country and the number of teams in each finals tournament (in brackets) are shown.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The objective of the game is to score more goals than the opposing team by moving the ball beyond the goal line into a rectangular-framed goal defended by the opponent.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Traditionally, the game has been played over two 45-minute halves, for a total match time of 90 minutes.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] With an estimated 250 million players active in over 200 countries and territories, it is the world's most popular sport.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Association football is played in accordance with the Laws of the Game, a set of rules that has been in effect since 1863 and maintained by the International Football Association Board (IFAB) since 1886.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The game is played with a football that is 68–70 cm (27–28 in) in circumference.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] When the ball is in play, the players mainly use their feet, but may also use any other part of their body, except for their hands or arms, to control, strike, or pass the ball; the head, chest, and thighs are commonly used.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Only the goalkeepers may use their hands and arms, but only within their own penalty area.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Depending on the format of the competition, an equal number of goals scored may result in a draw being declared with 1 point awarded to each team, or the game may go into extra time or a penalty shoot-out.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Internationally, association football is governed by FIFA.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Under FIFA, there are six continental confederations: AFC, CAF, CONCACAF, CONMEBOL, OFC, and UEFA.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] National associations (e.g. the FA in England, U.S.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Soccer in the United States, etc.) are responsible for managing the game in their own countries both professionally and at an amateur level, and coordinating competitions in accordance with the Laws of the Game.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The most prestigious senior international competition is the FIFA World Cup.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The men's World Cup is the most-viewed sporting event in the world, surpassing the Olympic Games.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The most prestigious competition in European club football is the UEFA Champions League, which attracts an extensive television audience worldwide.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The final of the men's Champions League is the most-watched annual sporting event in the world.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Association football is part of a family of football games that emerged from various ball games played worldwide since antiquity.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The word "association" in this term refers to the Football Association (the FA), founded in London in 1863, which published the first set of rules for the sport that same year.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The term was coined to distinguish the type of football played in accordance with the FA rules from other types that were gaining popularity at the time, particularly rugby football.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The term *soccer* comes from Oxford "-er" slang, which was prevalent at the University of Oxford in England from about 1875, and is thought to have been borrowed from the slang of Rugby School.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Initially spelt *assoccer* (a shortening of "association"), it was later reduced to the modern spelling.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Early alternative spellings included *socca* and *socker*.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] This form of slang also gave rise to *rugger* for rugby football, *fiver* and *tenner* for five pound and ten pound notes, and the now-archaic *footer* that was also a name for association football.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] A notable exception is New Zealand, where in the first two decades of the 21st century, under the influence of international television, "football" has been gaining prevalence, despite the dominance of other types of football, namely rugby union and rugby league.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] FIFA has stated that soccer originated in Britain, starting around the eighth century, and that no historical connection exists with any game played in antiquity outside Europe.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The modern rules of association football are based on the mid-19th century efforts to standardise the widely varying forms of football played in the public schools of England.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Kicking ball games arose independently multiple times across multiple cultures.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The Chinese competitive game **cuju** (蹴鞠, literally "kickball"; also known as *tsu chu*) resembles modern association football as well as a mix of basketball and volleyball.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] This is the earliest form of a kicking game for which there is historical evidence.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The game was first recorded as in exercise in the Zhan Guo Ce, a military history from the Han dynasty.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] **Cuju** players would pass the ball around, having to avoid it touching the ground at any point.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] It was then passed to a designated player, who attempted to kick it through the *fengliu yan*, a circular goal atop 10–11 meter poles.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] During the Han dynasty (206 BCE – 220 CE), **cuju** games were standardised and rules were established.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The Silk Road facilitated the transmission of *cuju* outside of China, especially the form of the game popular in the Tang dynasty, the period when the inflatable ball was invented and replaced the stuffed ball.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Other East Asian games include **kemari** in Japan and **chuk-guk** in Korea, both influenced by *cuju*.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] **Kemari** originated after the year 600 during the Asuka period.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] It was a ceremonial rather than a competitive game, and involved the kicking of a *mari*, a ball made of animal skin.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In North America, *pasuckuakohowog* was a ball game played by the Algonquians; it was described as "almost identical to the kind of folk football being played in Europe at the same time, in which the ball was kicked through goals".
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In the Middle Ages, one notable game with similarities to modern football was *calcio storico fiorentino*, which originated in Florence, Italy.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Another medieval sport that can be considered a form of early football is *la soule* (or *choule*), played in France from the 12th century, in which the ball was propelled by hands, feet, and sticks.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] As with pre-codified mob football, the antecedent of all modern football codes, these medieval games involved more handling of the ball than kicking it.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The Cambridge rules, first drawn up at the University of Cambridge in 1848, were particularly influential in the development of subsequent codes, including association football.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The Cambridge rules were written at Trinity College, Cambridge, at a meeting attended by representatives from Eton, Harrow, Rugby, Winchester, and Shrewsbury schools.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] During the 1850s, many clubs unconnected to schools or universities were formed throughout the English-speaking world to play various forms of football.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Some came up with their own distinct codes of rules, most notably the Sheffield Football Club, formed by former public school pupils in 1857, which led to the formation of a Sheffield FA in 1867.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In 1862, John Charles Thring of Uppingham School also devised an influential set of rules.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] These ongoing efforts contributed to the formation of the Football Association (the FA) in 1863, which first met on the morning of 26 October 1863 at the Freemasons' Tavern in Great Queen Street, London.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The only school to be represented on this occasion was Charterhouse.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The Freemasons' Tavern was the setting for five more meetings of the FA between October and December 1863; the English FA eventually issued the first comprehensive set of rules named Laws of the Game, forming modern football.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The laws included bans on running with the ball in hand and hacking (kicking an opponent in the shins), tripping and holding.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Eleven clubs, under the charge of FA secretary Ebenezer Cobb Morley, ratified the original thirteen laws of the game.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The sticking point was hacking, which a twelfth club at the meeting, Blackheath FC, had wanted to keep, resulting in their withdrawal from the FA.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Other English rugby clubs followed this lead and did not join the FA, and instead in 1871, along with Blackheath, formed the Rugby Football Union.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The 1863 FA rules included handling of the ball by "marks" and the lack of a crossbar, making the game remarkably similar to Victorian rules football, which was being developed around the same time in Australia.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The Sheffield FA played by its own rules until the 1870s, with the FA absorbing some of its rules until there was little difference between the games.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The world's oldest football competition is the FA Cup, which was founded by the footballer and cricketer Charles W.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Alcock, and has been contested by English teams since 1872.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The first official international football match also took place in 1872, between Scotland and England in Glasgow, again at the instigation of Alcock.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] England is also home to the world's first football league, which was founded in Birmingham in 1888 by Aston Villa director William McGregor.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The original format contained 12 clubs from the Midlands and Northern England.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The Laws of the Game are determined by the International Football Association Board (IFAB).
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The board was formed in 1886 after a meeting in Manchester of the Football Association, the Scottish Football Association, the Football Association of Wales, and the Irish Football Association.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] FIFA, the international football body, was formed in Paris in 1904 and declared that they would adhere to the Laws of the Game of the Football Association.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The growing popularity of the international game led to the admittance of FIFA representatives to the IFAB in 1913.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The board consists of four representatives from FIFA and one representative from each of the four British associations.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] For most of the 20th century, Europe and South America were the dominant regions in association football.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The FIFA World Cup, inaugurated in 1930, became the main stage for players of both continents to show their worth and the strength of their national teams.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In the second half of the century, the European Cup and the Copa Libertadores were created, and the champions of these two club competitions would contest the Intercontinental Cup to prove which team was the best in the world.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In the 21st century, South America has continued to produce some of the best footballers in the world, but its clubs have fallen behind the still dominant European clubs, which often sign the best players from Latin America and elsewhere.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Meanwhile, football has improved in Africa, Asia, and North America, and nowadays, these regions are at least on equal grounds with South America in club football.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Football is played at a professional level all over the world.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Millions of people regularly go to football stadiums to follow their favourite teams, whilst billions more watch the game on television or on the internet.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] A very large number of people also play football at an amateur level.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] According to a survey conducted by FIFA published in 2001, over 240 million people from more than 200 countries regularly play football.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Football has the highest global television audience in sport.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In many parts of the world, football evokes great passions and plays an important role in the life of individual fans, local communities, and even nations.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Ryszard Kapuściński says that Europeans who are polite, modest, or humble fall easily into rage when playing or watching football games.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] By contrast, football is widely considered to have been the final proximate cause for the Football War in June 1969 between El Salvador and Honduras.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The sport also exacerbated tensions at the beginning of the Croatian War of Independence of the 1990s, when a match between Dinamo Zagreb and Red Star Belgrade degenerated into rioting in May 1990.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The popularity of association football has been connected to identity fusion with replacement fandom collective identities.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Women's association football has historically seen opposition, with national associations severely curbing its development and several outlawing it completely.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Nevertheless, women have been playing football and similar games for as long as such games have existed.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Frescoes from the Han dynasty (25–220 CE) depict female figures playing the ancient Chinese game *cuju*.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] There are also reports of annual football matches played by women in Midlothian, Scotland, during the 1790s.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] There is documented evidence of women's early involvement in association football.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Informal matches between Scotland and England are reported to have taken place in 1881, but are not officially recognised by the respective football associations.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The first women's match recorded by the Scottish Football Association took place in 1892 in Glasgow.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In England, the first recorded game of football between women took place in 1895.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The best-documented early European team was founded by activist Nettie Honeyball in England in 1894: the British Ladies' Football Club.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Honeyball considered women's involvement in football as part of the emancipation movement.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] She and others like her paved the way for women's football.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] However, the women's game was frowned upon by the British football associations and continued without their support.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] It has been suggested that this was motivated by a perceived threat to the "masculinity" of the game.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Women's football became popular on a large scale at the time of the First World War, when female employment in heavy industry spurred the growth of the game, much as it had done for men decades earlier.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The most successful team of the era was Dick, Kerr Ladies F.C. of Preston, England.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] They played in one of the first women's international matches against a French XI team in 1920, and also made up most of the England team against a Scottish Ladies XI in the same year, winning 22–0.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In the early 20th century, women's football in the United Kingdom was mostly associated with charity matches.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Players and football writers have argued that this ban was, in fact, due to envy of the large crowds that women's matches attracted, and because the FA had no control over the money made from the women's game.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The FA ban led to the formation of the short-lived English Ladies Football Association and play moved to rugby grounds.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Women's football also faced bans in several other countries, notably in Brazil from 1941 to 1979, in France from 1941 to 1970, and in West Germany from 1955 to 1970.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In spite of the resistance from governing bodies, British women continued to play football.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Restrictions against female participation in the sport began to be reduced in the late 1960s and the 1970s.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The Italian women's football league was established in 1968.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In December 1969, the Women's Football Association was formed in England, with the sport eventually becoming the most prominent team sport for women in the United Kingdom.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Two unofficial women's World Cups were organised by the FIEFF in 1970 and in 1971.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Also in 1971, UEFA members voted to officially recognise women's football, while the Football Association rescinded the ban that prohibited women from playing on association members' pitches in England.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The first Asian Women's Championship happened in 1975, initially without the approval of the AFC, but later recognised by them.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Women's football still faces many struggles, but its worldwide growth has seen major competitions being launched at both the national and international levels, mirroring the men's competitions.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The FIFA Women's World Cup was inaugurated in 1991: the first tournament was held in China, featuring 12 teams from the six confederations.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The World Cup has been held every four years since; by 2019, it had expanded to 24 national teams, and 1.12 billion viewers watched the competition.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Four years later, FIFA targeted the 32-team 2023 Women's World Cup at an audience of 2 billion, while more than 1.5 million tickets were sold, setting a Women's World Cup record.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Women's football has been an Olympic event since 1996.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] North America is the dominant region in women's football, with the United States winning the most FIFA Women's World Cups and Olympic tournaments.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Europe and Asia come second and third in terms of international success, and the women's game has been improving in South America.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Association football is played in accordance with a set of rules known as the Laws of the Game.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The game is played using a spherical ball of 68–70 cm (27–28 in) circumference, known as the *football* (or *soccer ball*).
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Two teams of eleven players each compete to get the ball into the other team's goal (between the posts and under the bar), thereby scoring a goal.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] There are situations where a goal can be disallowed, such as an offside call or a foul in the build-up to the goal.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The team that has scored more goals at the end of the game is the winner; if both teams have scored an equal number of goals then the game is a draw.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Each team is led by a captain who has only one official responsibility as mandated by the Laws of the Game: to represent their team in the coin toss before kick-off or penalty kicks.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The primary law is that players other than goalkeepers may not deliberately handle the ball with their hands or arms during play, though they must use both their hands during a throw-in restart.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Although players usually use their feet to move the ball around, they may use any part of their body (notably, "heading" with the forehead) other than their hands or arms.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Within normal play, all players are free to play the ball in any direction and move throughout the pitch, though players may not pass to teammates who are in an offside position.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] During gameplay, players attempt to create goal-scoring opportunities through individual control of the ball, such as by dribbling, passing the ball to a teammate, and by taking shots at the goal, which is guarded by the opposing goalkeeper.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Opposing players may try to regain control of the ball by intercepting a pass or through tackling the opponent in possession of the ball; however, physical contact between opponents is restricted.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Football is generally a free-flowing game, with play stopping only when the ball has left the field of play or when play is stopped by the referee for an infringement of the rules.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] After a stoppage, play recommences with a specified restart.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] At a professional level, most matches produce only a few goals.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] For example, the 2022–23 season of the English Premier League produced an average of 2.85 goals per match.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The Laws of the Game do not specify any player positions other than goalkeeper, but a number of specialised roles have evolved.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Broadly, these include three main categories: strikers, or forwards, whose main task is to score goals; defenders, who specialise in preventing their opponents from scoring; and midfielders, who dispossess the opposition and keep possession of the ball to pass it to the forwards on their team.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Players in these positions are referred to as outfield players, to distinguish them from the goalkeeper.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] These positions are further subdivided according to the area of the field in which the player spends the most time.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] For example, there are central defenders and left and right midfielders.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The ten outfield players may be arranged in any combination.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The number of players in each position determines the style of the team's play; more forwards and fewer defenders creates a more aggressive and offensive-minded game, while the reverse creates a slower, more defensive style of play.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] While players typically spend most of the game in a specific position, there are few restrictions on player movement, and players can switch positions at any time.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The layout of a team's players is known as a *formation*.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Defining the team's formation and tactics is usually the prerogative of the team's manager.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] There are seventeen laws in the official Laws of the Game, each containing a collection of stipulations and guidelines.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The same laws are designed to apply to all levels of football for both sexes, although certain modifications for groups such as juniors, seniors and people with physical disabilities are permitted.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The laws are often framed in broad terms, which allow flexibility in their application depending on the nature of the game.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The Laws of the Game are published by FIFA, but are maintained by the IFAB.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In addition to the seventeen laws, numerous IFAB decisions and other directives contribute to the regulation of association football.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Within the United States, Major League Soccer used a distinct ruleset during the 1990s, and the NFHS and NCAA still use rulesets that are comparable to, but different from, the IFAB Laws.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Each team consists of a maximum of eleven players (excluding substitutes), one of whom must be the goalkeeper.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Competition rules may state a minimum number of players required to constitute a team, which is usually seven.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Goalkeepers are the only players allowed to play the ball with their hands or arms, provided they do so within the penalty area in front of their own goal.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Though there are a variety of positions in which the outfield (non-goalkeeper) players are strategically placed by a coach, these positions are not defined or required by the Laws.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The basic equipment or *kit* players are required to wear includes a shirt, shorts, socks, footwear and adequate shin guards.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Wearing an athletic supporter with protective cup is recommended for male players by medical experts and professionals.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Headgear is not a required piece of equipment, but players may choose to wear it to protect themselves from head injury.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Players are forbidden to wear or use anything that is dangerous to themselves or another player, such as jewellery or watches.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The goalkeeper must wear clothing that is easily distinguishable from that worn by the other players and the match officials.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] A number of players may be replaced by substitutes during the course of the game.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The maximum number of substitutions permitted in most competitive international and domestic league games is five in 90 minutes, with each team being allowed one more if the game should go into extra-time; the permitted number may vary in other competitions or in friendly matches.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Common reasons for a substitution include injury, tiredness, ineffectiveness, a tactical switch, or timewasting at the end of a finely poised game.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In standard adult matches, a player who has been substituted may not take further part in a match.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] IFAB recommends "that a match should not continue if there are fewer than seven players in either team".
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Any decision regarding points awarded for abandoned games is left to the individual football associations.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] A game is officiated by a referee, who has "full authority to enforce the Laws of the Game in connection with the match to which he has been appointed" (Law 5), and whose decisions are final.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The referee is assisted by two assistant referees.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In many high-level games there is also a fourth official who assists the referee and may replace another official should the need arise.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Goal line technology is used to measure if the whole ball has crossed the goal-line thereby determining whether a goal has been scored or not; this was brought in to prevent controversy.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Video assistant referees (VAR) have also been increasingly introduced in high-level matches to assist officials through video replays to correct clear and obvious mistakes.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] There are four types of calls that can be reviewed: mistaken identity in awarding a red or yellow card, goals and whether there was a violation during the build-up, direct red card decisions, and penalty decisions.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The ball is spherical with a circumference of between 68 and 70 cm (27 and 28 in), a weight in the range of 410 to 450 g (14 to 16 oz), and a pressure between 0.6 and 1.1 standard atmospheres (8.5 and 15.6 pounds per square inch) at sea level.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In the past the ball was made up of leather panels sewn together, with a latex bladder for pressurisation, but modern balls at all levels of the game are now synthetic.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] As the Laws were formulated in England, and were initially administered solely by the four British football associations within IFAB, the standard dimensions of a football pitch were originally expressed in imperial units.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The Laws now express dimensions with approximate metric equivalents (followed by traditional units in brackets), though use of imperial units remains popular in English-speaking countries with a relatively recent history of metrication (or only partial metrication), such as Britain.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The length of the pitch, or field, for international adult matches is in the range of 100–110 m (110–120 yd) and the width is in the range of 64–75 m (70–80 yd).
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Fields for non-international matches may be 90–120 m (100–130 yd) in length and 45–90 m (50–100 yd) in width, provided the pitch does not become square.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In 2008, the IFAB initially approved a fixed size of 105 m (115 yd) long and 68 m (74 yd) wide as a standard pitch dimension for international matches; however, this decision was later put on hold and was never actually implemented.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The longer boundary lines are *touchlines*, while the shorter boundaries (on which the goals are placed) are *goal lines*.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] A rectangular goal is positioned on each goal line, midway between the two touchlines.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The inner edges of the vertical goal posts must be 7.32 m (24 ft) apart, and the lower edge of the horizontal crossbar supported by the goal posts must be 2.44 m (8 ft) above the ground.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Nets are usually placed behind the goal, but are not required by the Laws.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In front of the goal is the penalty area.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] This area is marked by the goal line, two lines starting on the goal line 16.5 m (18 yd) from the goalposts and extending 16.5 m (18 yd) into the pitch perpendicular to the goal line, and a line joining them.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] This area has a number of functions, the most prominent being to mark where the goalkeeper may handle the ball and where a penalty foul by a member of the defending team becomes punishable by a penalty kick.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Other markings define the position of the ball or players at kick-offs, goal kicks, penalty kicks and corner kicks.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] A standard adult football match consists of two halves of 45 minutes each.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Each half runs continuously, meaning that the clock is not stopped when the ball is out of play.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] There is usually a 15-minute half-time break between halves.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The end of the match is known as full-time.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The referee is the official timekeeper for the match, and may make an allowance for time lost through substitutions, injured players requiring attention, or other stoppages.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] This added time is called "additional time" in FIFA documents, but is most commonly referred to as *stoppage time* or *injury time*, while *lost time* can also be used as a synonym.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The duration of stoppage time is at the sole discretion of the referee.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Stoppage time does not fully compensate for the time in which the ball is out of play, and a 90-minute game typically involves about an hour of "effective playing time".
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The referee alone signals the end of the match.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In matches where a fourth official is appointed, towards the end of the half, the referee signals how many minutes of stoppage time they intend to add.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The fourth official then informs the players and spectators by holding up a board showing this number.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The signalled stoppage time may be further extended by the referee.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Added time was introduced because of an incident in 1891 during a match between Stoke and Aston Villa.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Trailing 1–0 with two minutes remaining, Stoke were awarded a penalty kick.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Villa's goalkeeper deliberately kicked the ball far out of play; by the time it was recovered, the clock had run out and the game was over, leaving Stoke unable to attempt the penalty.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The same rule also states that the duration of either half is extended until a penalty kick to be taken or retaken is completed; thus, no game can end with an uncompleted penalty.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Due to the relatively high ambient temperatures in some regions, cooling breaks for the players were introduced.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Breaks could take place at the referee's discretion after the 30th minute of each half if the wet-bulb globe temperature exceeded 32 °C (90 °F); the breaks would last 3 minutes, with this time made up by an extended period of stoppage time at the end of the half.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In league competitions, games may end in a draw.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In knockout competitions where a winner is required, various methods may be employed to break such a deadlock; some competitions may invoke replays.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] A game tied at the end of regulation time may go into extra time, which consists of two further 15-minute periods.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] If the score is still tied after extra time, some competitions allow the use of penalty shoot-outs (previously known in the Laws of the Game as "kicks from the penalty mark") to determine which team will progress to the next stage of the tournament or be the champion.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Goals scored during extra time periods count towards the final score of the game, but kicks from the penalty mark are only used to decide the team that progresses to the next part of the tournament, with goals scored in a penalty shoot-out not making up part of the final score.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In competitions using two-legged matches, each team competes at home once, with an aggregate score from the two matches deciding which team progresses.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Where aggregates are equal, the away goals rule may be used to determine the winners, in which case the winner is the team that scored the most goals in the leg they played away from home.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] If the result is still equal, extra time and potentially a penalty shoot-out are required.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Under the Laws, the two basic states of play during a game are *ball in play* and *ball out of play*.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] From the beginning of each playing period with a kick-off until the end of the playing period, the ball is in play at all times, except when either the ball leaves the field of play, or play is stopped by the referee.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Players are cautioned with a yellow card, and dismissed from the game with a red card.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] A foul occurs when a player commits an offence listed in the Laws of the Game while the ball is in play.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The offences that constitute a foul are listed in Law 12.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Handling the ball deliberately, tripping an opponent, or pushing an opponent, are examples of "penal fouls", punishable by a direct free kick or penalty kick depending on where the offence occurred.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Other fouls are punishable by an indirect free kick.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The referee may punish a player's or substitute's misconduct by a caution (yellow card) or dismissal (red card).
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] A second yellow card in the same game leads to a red card, which results in a dismissal.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] A player given a yellow card is said to have been "booked", the referee writing the player's name in their official notebook.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] If a player has been dismissed, no substitute can be brought on in their place and the player may not participate in further play.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Misconduct may occur at any time, and while the offences that constitute misconduct are listed, the definitions are broad.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In particular, the offence of "unsporting behaviour" may be used to deal with most events that violate the spirit of the game, even if they are not listed as specific offences.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] A referee can show a yellow or red card to a player, substitute, substituted player, and to non-players such as managers and support staff.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Rather than stopping play, the referee may allow play to continue if doing so will benefit the team against which an offence has been committed.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] This is known as "playing an advantage".
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The referee may "call back" play and penalise the original offence if the anticipated advantage does not ensue within "a few seconds".
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Even if an offence is not penalised due to advantage being played, the offender may still be sanctioned for misconduct at the next stoppage of play.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The referee's decision in all on-pitch matters is considered final.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The score of a match cannot be altered after the game, even if later evidence shows that decisions (including whether a goal was awarded or not) were incorrect.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Along with the general administration of the sport, football associations and competition organisers also enforce good conduct in wider aspects of the game, dealing with issues such as comments to the press, clubs' financial management, doping, age fraud and match fixing.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Most competitions enforce mandatory suspensions for players who are sent off in a game.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Some on-field incidents, if considered very serious (such as allegations of racial abuse), may result in competitions deciding to impose heavier sanctions than those normally associated with a red card.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Some associations allow for appeals against player suspensions incurred on-field if clubs feel a referee was incorrect or unduly harsh.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Sanctions for such infractions may be levied on individuals or on clubs as a whole.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Penalties may include fines, point deductions (in league competitions) or even expulsion from competitions.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] For example, the English Football League deduct 12 points from any team that enters financial administration.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Among other administrative sanctions are penalties against game forfeiture.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Teams that forfeit a game or are forfeited against are awarded a technical loss or win.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The recognised international governing body of football (and associated games, such as futsal and beach soccer) is FIFA.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The FIFA headquarters are located in Zürich, Switzerland.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] National associations (or national federations) oversee football within individual countries.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] 211 national associations are affiliated both with FIFA and with their respective continental confederations.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Other national associations may be members of continental confederations but otherwise not participate in FIFA competitions.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] While FIFA is responsible for organising international competitions and enforcing most international regulations, the Laws of the Game are set by the IFAB, where each of the four UK associations holds one vote and FIFA collectively holds four votes.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] International competitions in association football principally consist of two varieties: competitions involving representative national teams or those involving clubs based in multiple nations and national leagues.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] *International football*, without qualification, most often refers to the former.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In the case of international club competition, it is the country of origin of the clubs involved, not the nationalities of their players, that renders the competition international in nature.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The major international competition in football and the most prestigious is the World Cup, organised by FIFA.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] This competition has taken place every four years since 1930, with the exception of the 1942 and 1946 tournaments, which were cancelled because of World War II.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] As of 2022, over 200 national teams compete in qualifying tournaments within the scope of continental confederations for a place in the finals.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The finals tournament involved 32 national teams (expanding to 48 teams for the 2026 tournament) competing over a four-week period.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The World Cup is the world's most widely viewed and most followed sporting event, with the 2022 tournament estimated to be watched by 5 billion people, more than 60% of the global population.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The 1958 World Cup saw the emergence of Pelé as a global sporting star, a period that coincided with "the explosive spread of television, which massively amplified his presence everywhere".
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The current champions are Argentina, who won their third title at the 2022 tournament in Qatar.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The FIFA Women's World Cup has been held every four years since 1991.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Under the tournament's current format that was expanded in 2023, national teams vie for 31 slots in a three-year qualification phase, while the host nation's team enters automatically as the 32nd slot.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The current champions are Spain, after winning their first title in the 2023 tournament.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] There has been a football tournament at every Summer Olympic Games since 1900, except at the 1932 games in Los Angeles when FIFA and the International Olympic Committee (IOC) had disagreed over the status of amateur players.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Before the inception of the World Cup, the Olympics (especially during the 1920s) were the most prestigious international event.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Originally, the tournament was for amateurs only.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] As professionalism spread around the world, the gap in quality between the World Cup and the Olympics widened.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The countries that benefited most were the Soviet Bloc countries of Eastern Europe, where top athletes were state-sponsored while retaining their status as amateurs.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Between 1948 and 1980, 23 out of 27 Olympic medals were won by Eastern Europe, with only Sweden (gold in 1948 and bronze in 1952), Denmark (bronze in 1948 and silver in 1960) and Japan (bronze in 1968) breaking their dominance.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] For the 1984 Los Angeles Games, the IOC allowed professional players to compete.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Since 1992, male competitors must be under 23 years old, although since 1996, three players over the age of 23 have been allowed per squad.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] A women's tournament was added in 1996; in contrast to the men's event, full international sides without age restrictions play the women's Olympic tournament.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] After the World Cup, the most important international football competitions are the continental championships, which are organised by each continental confederation and contested between national teams.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] These are the European Championship (UEFA), the Copa América (CONMEBOL), the Africa Cup of Nations (CAF), the Asian Cup (AFC), the Gold Cup (CONCACAF) and the Nations Cup (OFC).
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] These competitions are not strictly limited to members of the continental confederations, with guest teams from other continents sometimes invited to compete.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The FIFA Confederations Cup was contested by the winners of all six continental championships, the current FIFA World Cup champions, and the country which was hosting the next World Cup.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] This was generally regarded as a warm-up tournament for the upcoming FIFA World Cup and did not carry the same prestige as the World Cup itself.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The tournament was discontinued following the 2017 edition, with its calendar slot replaced by an expanded FIFA Club World Cup.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The Finalissima was revived in 2022, and is contested between the Copa América and European Championship winners.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The UEFA Nations League and the CONCACAF Nations League were introduced in the late 2010s to replace international friendlies during the two-year cycle between major tournaments.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The most prestigious competitions in club football are the respective continental championships, which are generally contested between national champions, for example, the UEFA Champions League in Europe and the Copa Libertadores in South America.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The winners of each continental competition contest the FIFA Intercontinental Cup, held annually, and the FIFA Club World Cup, held once every four years.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In each country, football clubs are usually federated in associations or leagues that organise official tournaments among themselves, from which the champion of each country and the teams that will participate in international club tournaments emerge.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] There is no single system of competitions, and each national league organises them according to its own traditions.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The governing bodies in each country operate league systems in a domestic season, normally comprising several divisions, in which the teams gain points throughout the season depending on results, usually three points for a win, one for a draw and zero for a defeat.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Teams are put into tables, placed in order according to points accrued.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In the Old World (Africa, Asia and Europe), it is common for each team to play every other team in its league at home and away in each season, in a round-robin tournament.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] At the end of a season, which typically runs from August to May, the top team is declared the champion.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The top few teams may be promoted to a higher division, and one or more of the teams finishing at the bottom are relegated to a lower division.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The teams finishing at the top of a country's league may also be eligible to play in international club competitions in the following season.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Most countries supplement the league system with one or more "cup" competitions organised on a knock-out basis.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] These include the domestic cup, which may be open to all eligible teams in a country's league system—both professional and amateur—and is organised by the national federation.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Some countries' top divisions feature highly-paid star players; in smaller countries, lower divisions, and many women's clubs, players may be part-timers with a second job, or amateurs.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] The top five European leagues – Premier League (England), Bundesliga (Germany), La Liga (Spain), Serie A (Italy), and Ligue 1 (France) – attract most of the world's best players and, during the 2006–07 season, each of these leagues had a total wage cost in excess of €600 million.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] These leagues also generated a combined €17.2 billion in revenue in the 2021–22 season from television contracts, matchday tickets, sponsorships, and other sources.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In the 2022–23 season, clubs in Europe's "big five" leagues had an aggregate wage cost of €13 billion, with each league spending more than €1.8 billion in wages.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] In contrast, the combined revenue of these leagues was €19.6 billion.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Variants of association football have been codified for teams of reduced size, such as five-a-side football; for non-traditional playing environments, including beach soccer, futsal and indoor soccer; and for athletes with disabilities (Paralympic football).
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Street football can be played with only minimal equipment – a basic game can be played on almost any open area of reasonable size with just a ball made from almost any material and items to mark the positions of the goalposts.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/association-football] Such informal games can have team sizes that vary from eleven-a-side, can use a limited or modified subset of the official rules, and can be self-officiated by the players.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] The club's predecessor was called **Beijing Football Club** and they predominantly played in the top tier, where they won several domestic league and cup titles.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] On 29 December 1992, the club was recognized to become a completely professional football club, making them one of the founding members of the first fully professional top-tier league in China.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] Since then, they have gone on to win their first ever professional league title in the 2009 league season as well as the 1996, 1997, 2003, and 2018 Chinese FA Cup.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] According to *Forbes*, Guoan was the second most valuable football team in China, with a team value of US$167 million, and an estimated revenue of US$30 million in 2015.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] According to the disclosure of CITIC Pacific, the club revenue was CN¥244 million in the 2013 season.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] In the 2015 season, the sponsorship from CITIC Securities was CN¥25 million.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] The club's first incarnation came in 1951 when the local government sports body decided to take part in China's first fully national football league tournament.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] To prepare for the competition they participated in the 1951 North China Football Competition where they officially unveiled the team for the first time on 28 October 1951.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] After this tournament the relevant parties decided to form a football team with the best players from Beijing and Tianjin to create the North China team who were unveiled on 1 December 1951 for the start of the national football league tournament.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] The team name was taken from the football team in the 1910 multi-sport event Chinese National Games that also represented the same regions.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] The team ended up finishing fourth in their debut season and with the football league gradually expanding, the players from Beijing and Tianjin were allowed to separate and the local Beijing government sports body was allowed to reform the club as Beijing Football Club in 1955.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] The club made its debut appearance in the 1956 season and wore an all-white home kit and all-red away strip.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] In the 1956 campaign, the club was also allowed to enter their youth team called Beijing Youth B, who actually went on to win the league title while Beijing came sixth that season.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] The club strengthened their hold on the following seasons when they won the 1957 and 1958 league titles.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] With these results, the club had become a major force within Chinese football, and with the club's youth team still participating within the top tier, there was a constant supply of players coming into the team to fight for places.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] Being China's capital city and for their success on the field, the club had become a feeder team for the Chinese national team.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] When football returned to China, Beijing won the 1973 league title in the newly re-established footballing league.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] While Beijing once again re-established themselves as major title contenders, they did not win any major titles until 1982, where they won the league title, followed by the 1984 league title and the 1985 Chinese FA Cup title.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] After this period, Beijing's performances seemed to have declined and were relegated for the first time in their history to the second tier at the end of the 1988 season.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] However, their time within the second tier was short-lived and they won the division title and promotion to the first tier at the end of the 1990 season.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] In total, Beijing had won the league title five times during the old Chinese National Football League era before the club was given full professionalism in 1992.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] Beijing Guoan was formed on 29 December 1992, as a result of the Chinese football reform, which was the Chinese Football Association's attempt to professionalize the Chinese football league system.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] The club was set up by CITIC Guoan of CITIC Group, a state-owned enterprise of China, and the Beijing Municipal Sports Committee.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] The club then took part in the 1994 Chinese Jia-A League season, making them a founding member of the first fully professional top-tier league in China and changed their home colors to green to symbolize the change.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] In their first professional season, Beijing finished in a disappointing eighth out of twelve teams and club manager Tang Pengju was relieved of his duties.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] The club brought in Jin Zhiyang to manage them the following season and the results under his reign improved enough for them to finish the 1995 campaign in the runner-up position.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] The following season, Jin Zhiyang lead Beijing to their first professional trophy when they beat Jinan Taishan Jiangjun 4–1 to win the 1996 Chinese FA Cup.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] Jin Zhiyang was able to retain the Cup the following year with a 2–1 victory against Shanghai Shenhua, which impressed the Chinese FA, who lured him away from Beijing when they offered him a position with the Chinese national team.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] Assistant coach Shen Xiangfu stepped into the managerial role and in his debut season, he guided the club to third within the league.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] However, in his second season the team slid down to sixth and he left the club.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] Serbian Milovan Đorić became Beijing's first foray with a foreign manager when he joined the club at the start of the 2000 league season.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] His reign was exceptionally short-lived after he lost his first three games of the season before he was replaced with native coach Wei Kexing.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] At the start of the 2002 league season, Beijing hired their second foreign manager in Ljupko Petrović.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] Foreign influences continued in 2003, when the club signed a three-year endorsement contract with jointly owned South Korean company Beijing Hyundai, which resulted in the club changing its name to Beijing Hyundai to accommodate this.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] In 2005, Spanish football club Real Madrid went into negotiations with Beijing on a football development project.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] At the start of the 2007 league season, two-time Chinese FA Cup winner with Chongqing Lifan and Qingdao Beilaite, Lee Jang-soo, was hired as the team's manager.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] The South Korean manager, in his debut season, guided the club to second within the league.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] By the 2009 league season, the club had returned to the Workers Stadium (after it had been in renovation for the 2008 Summer Olympics) under Lee Jang-soo's helm.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] It looked as if the club would be winning its first professional league title until a 2–0 defeat from Changchun Yatai on 15 September 2009, which saw the club slip to third place and Lee Jang-soo was unscrupulously fired with seven games remaining.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] Former Beijing player Hong Yuanshuo was immediately brought into the team and on the final day of the season, Beijing thrashed Hangzhou Greentown 4–0 to clinch the 2009 league championship.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] In 2026, Beijing started the 2026 Chinese Super League season with five points deducted for violation of sports ethics and loss of sportsmanship, engaging in improper transactions to seek illegitimate benefits.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] The club issued a defiant statement on its social media account which read, "Heaven sees all!
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] (Chinese: *人在做，天在看！头顶三尺有神明!*)", without acknowledging or admitting to any wrongdoing.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] Despite being founded by CITIC Guoan Group, the stake of the football club was held by another subsidiary, CITIC Corp., Ltd.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] (Chinese: 中国中信股份有限公司) of CITIC Group, a Beijing-incorporated SPV, for a possible listing in mainland China since 2012.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] (CITIC Group invited other investors to purchase the new shares of CITIC Guoan Group in 2014, making the company no longer a subsidiary of CITIC Group).
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] In 2014, CITIC Group floated, by backdoor listing, most of their assets to their Hong Kong-based subsidiary CITIC Pacific (renaming it to CITIC Limited), including the entire share capital of "CITIC Corp.", thus the stake of the football club was indirectly floated in a stock exchange.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] On 27 December 2016, real estate company Sinobo Group participated in the capital increase of the club for a reported 64% stake, which was finalised on 10 January 2017, making them the largest shareholder.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] According to a Chinese Government database, the share capital of the club had increased from CN¥75 million to CN¥208.33 million, making Sinobo Group own a 64.00% stake with CN¥133.33 million par value and undisclosed share premium.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] The club was also renamed to **Beijing Sinobo Guoan F.C.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] Beijing Guoan's fiercest and oldest rivalry is against Shanghai Shenhua and is often referred to as the Jing-Hu derby, or the rivalry between Beijing and Shanghai.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] The rivalry with Shenhua is viewed as a manifestation of the rivalry that exists between the cities which are the most important for the nation, as one is the center of government while the other is the financial centre.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] With each club being able to claim an extensive history spanning successful periods, direct competition for silverware, however, rarely coincided until the 1997 league season.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] With Shenhua having won the 1995 league title and Beijing having won the 1996 Chinese FA Cup, both teams looked as if they had the pedigree to win silverware that season and on 20 July 1997, in a vital league game, Beijing thrashed Shenhua 9–1 at the Workers' Stadium in Beijing.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] It was Beijing's largest victory and Shenhua's greatest defeat ever recorded.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] Soon after that match, both teams met again in the 1997 FA Cup final, which saw Beijing win the cup.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] Between 2010 and 2024, Beijing Guoan held a record of twelve straight wins over Shanghai Shenhua at the Workers' Stadium, Beijing Guoan's home ground.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] The Jing-Jin derby is a local and long-standing rivalry between Beijing Guoan and neighboring Tianjin Jinmen Tiger.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] Both teams can trace their histories to the North China team before it split to form the Beijing Football Club and Tianjin Football Club.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] Note: Flags indicate national team as defined under FIFA eligibility rules; some limited exceptions apply.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] Players may hold more than one non-FIFA nationality.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] All-time honours list, including semi-professional Beijing period.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-guoan-f-c] On neutral venues, the scores for Beijing F.C. are written first.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] The club was founded in Pudong District, Shanghai on 3 February 1995 and were originally known as Shanghai Pudong before they made their debut in the third tier of China's football league pyramid in the 1995 season.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] They would work their way up to the top tier while changing name to accommodate their sponsors.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] In the 2006 season the club would relocate the team to Shaanxi and rename themselves Xi'an Chanba International, however by the 2012 season, the club relocated this time to Guizhou, and changed their name to Guizhou Renhe.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] In the 2016 season the club relocated the team to Fengtai District, Beijing, and changed their name to Beijing Renhe.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] Throughout the club's history their greatest achievement has been winning the 2013 Chinese FA Cup while the highest position they have ever finished was second within the 2003 season.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] The club was founded on 3 February 1995 in Pudong District, Shanghai to take part in the recently formed fully professional football league system and they started at the bottom of the football pyramid in the third division, where they named themselves Shanghai Pudong.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] Playing in all blue in their debut season, they would immediately taste success when they won the division title and promotion to the second tier.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] The following seasons, however, saw the team languish within the division until they brought in Xu Genbao to manage the side at the beginning of the 2000 season and would make the club promotion contenders.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] Under Xu Genbao's leadership, they didn't have to wait long to win promotion when they would go on to win the division title at the end of the season and a chance to play in the top tier.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] Under the ownership of Shanghai Yungtay Engineering and COSCO Real Estate, the club rebranded themselves with a new blue and white striped football kit.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] They were big spenders who wanted to achieve immediate success by bringing in established Chinese internationals such as Cheng Yaodong, Jiang Jin and particularly Wu Chengying who set a Chinese transfer fee record of 13,000,000 RMB.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] This saw them become genuine title contenders and under their new manager Cheng Yaodong, they would fight for the league title with Shanghai Greenland Shenhua and only come second by a single point at the end of the 2003 season.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] The owners could not maintain the level of spending that they had done and the team's results would start to slip.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] Finding that they could not compete with Shanghai Shenhua and in the 2005 season, they had to face additional competition in Shanghai Zobon, the team decided to move to Xi'an after months of speculation.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] With the newly branded team known as Shanghai International, they would start to move away from the previous Yuanshen Stadium in Shanghai to the Shaanxi Province Stadium in Xi'an, Shaanxi Province and rename themselves Xi'an Chanba International by 2006.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] In 2007, their ownership was transferred to Baorong Investment and it was during this period that the club would start to experiment with a new yellow football kit.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] This would surprisingly seem to work when the club looked as if they were title contenders once more during the 2008 season, however their title hopes quickly faded and the team eventually finished fifth.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] The following season, however, would see the team languish near the bottom of the table and Cheng Yaodong decided to resign, which would see former Chinese national football coach Zhu Guanghu come in and guide the team away from the relegation zone.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] At the beginning of the 2010 season, Dai Yongge and the Renhe Commercial Holdings Company started to invest heavily within the club.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] This would see the club bring in Chinese internationals Sun Jihai, Zhao Xuri, Qu Bo and Mao Jianqing into the team.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] However, despite the signings, the club struggled within the league and Zhu Guanghu left the club while three time Chinese league winner Milorad Kosanović replaced him.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] Milorad Kosanović's reign at the club was unsuccessful and he was soon replaced by Slobodan Santrač.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] After a poor string of results, Slobodan Santrač was fired and former Chinese international manager Gao Hongbo came into the club while it languished in mid-table throughout much of the 2011 season.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] The 2012 season saw Guizhou have a successful year, with the club achieving fourth place and gaining entry into its first AFC Champions League.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] The team's success continued as they qualified for the 2014 AFC Champions League as well, but got knocked out in the group stage both times they qualified.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] Their top achievements in this period included winning the 2014 Chinese FA Super Cup and the 2013 Chinese FA Cup.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] In the 2015 season they were relegated to the League One, but the team managed to advance back to the Super League in 2018.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] In 2016 they moved from Guizhou to Beijing, becoming Beijing Renhe.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] After one season where they placed eighth, in 2019 the club struggled to win games and found themselves in last place with a few rounds to go.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] Having lost their 2020 China League One relegation play-off matches 2–3 on aggregate to Jiangxi Liansheng, Beijing Renhe were relegated to the League Two.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] They changed their name to Beijing Chengfeng to meet Chinese Football Association's "neutral name" requirement, before the dissolution of the club on 29 March 2021.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] When the club originated their home colours would predominantly be blue until the club won promotion to the top tier and decided that they needed to differentiate themselves from their local rivals Shanghai Greenland Shenhua, who also play in blue.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] This saw them employ a blue and white stripe top at the beginning of the 2003 league season and a new crest design of a horse in front of a striped background which was directly inspired by Juventus FC own logo.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] When the club was bought out by Baorong Investments who moved the club to Xi'an they decided that the club should use a new yellow top by the beginning of the 2008 league season and a new crest of a wolf was employed.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] When the club was founded in Shanghai they decided to take advantage of the 1994 Chinese football league professionalism reforms that allowed more than one club in each city.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] With Shanghai Shenhua already established within the city the potential for China's first top-flight city derby emerged.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] On 9 March 2002 the first top-flight city derby became a reality when they met in a league game, which saw the club win 2–0 away to Shenhua in front of a sold out Hongkou Football Stadium.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] Known as the Shanghai derby it would be the start of an intense but short rivalry between the two clubs, which reached its peak on the final day of the 2003 league season with both teams able to win the league title.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] Shenhua won their game while the club surprisingly lost theirs to relegation fighting club Tianjin TEDA.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] This saw critics dispute the title win and it was eventually discovered that both teams had players and officials match-fix games throughout the campaign.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] Shenhua would retrospectively lose their title while the club owners decided it was financially unviable to remain in Shanghai and relocated their team to Xi'an, which effectively ended the rivalry.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/beijing-renhe-f-c] Managers who have coached the club and team since Guizhou Renhe was formed.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/china-national-football-b-team] Before Joining FIFA, the Chinese national football team's main duty was to play friendlies with friendly countries.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/china-national-football-b-team] Sometimes a B team was created when the national team was occupied elsewhere.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/china-national-football-b-team] There was no obvious age or skill difference between the A and B teams.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/china-national-football-b-team] In 1957, the national white team was defeated by the national red team and lost the ticket to Melbourne.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/china-national-football-b-team] After the defeat, the national white team was regarded as the national B team before relegating to a regional team, the Tianjin Football Team.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/china-national-football-b-team] More B teams were created from time and time since.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/china-national-football-b-team] Chinese Football Association organised a China B team in 1981 with the name of *China Hope* in order to provide more international experiences for the young talents of the league.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/china-national-football-b-team] The team was dissolved in 1982 after a brawl with the Tunisia national football team.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/china-national-football-b-team] In 1984 another B team was established, coached by Zhang Jingtian.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/china-national-football-b-team] In 1986 a third national team, the national yellow team was created based on the championship team Liaoning FC.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/china-national-football-b-team] The B team sometimes compete in the CFA leagues and won the league title in 1989 under the coaching of Xu Genbao.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/china-national-football-b-team] In the same year FIFA and IOC agreed to limit soccer players participating in the Olympics to be under 23, and the China B was rebranded as the China national under-23 football team.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/china-national-football-b-team] On 2 May 2017, a new China B team was reorganised by China national football team manager Marcello Lippi.
[src:china-national-football-b-team/china-national-football-b-team] The following players have been called up within the last twelve months.
